<section xml:id="linked-lists_simple-linked-list-improvements"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Improvements for SimpleLinkedList</title>

  <p>
    We have already identified some improvements that could be made to our SimpleLinkedList class. One simple addition we mentioned would be to add a <pf>size</pf> variable that keeps track of how many elements are in the list. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Adding a <pf>size</pf> variable would provide a few benefits.
    Currently, to find the size of the list, we would need to loop through all the nodes and count them. (This would take <m>O(n)</m> time.) If we kept a <pf>size</pf> variable updated as we add and remove elements, we could return the size in constant time, <m>O(1)</m>. We could also use the <pf>size</pf> variable to help with bounds checking when asked to access a particular index.
  </p>

  <p>
    Adding a <pf>size</pf> variable will add a slight amount of complexity to our code. We will need to remember to update the <pf>size</pf> variable whenever we add or remove an element. But the performance benefits, and the ability to easily check bounds, make it worth the extra complexity.
  </p>

  <insight>
    <p>Usually we want to avoid storing the same data more than once. We already implicitly are storing the size of the list by the number of nodes it contains, so adding a <pf>size</pf> variable is a form of data duplication.</p>
    <p>But, there are cases where the benefits of having that data readily available outweigh the cost of duplication. Unless we don't care about providing a <pf>size()</pf> function, or using indexes in our list, adding a <pf>size</pf> variable is a reasonable trade-off.</p>
  </insight>

  <p>
    Another issue we have not addressed yet is working at the end of the list. Currently, if we want to add an element to the end of the list, we have to start at the head and walk through all the nodes until we reach the end. This takes <m>O(n)</m> time. If we kept a pointer to the tail node of the list, we could add elements to the end in constant time, <m>O(1)</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Below is an animation of what using a tail pointer to add a new element to the end of the list would look like.
  </p>

  <activity>
    <title>Singly Linked List with Tail Pointer</title>
    <p>
      This version of the linked list keeps track of the size of the list and a tail pointer to the last node in the list. It has started to insert 20 at the end of the list. Use <c> > </c> to step through the process.
    </p>
    <interactive platform="javascript" 
                design-width="1600"
                 aspect="4:2.5">
    <script type="module">
      import { LinkedListTail } from "./external/interactives/data-structures/entry.js";

      let anim = new LinkedListTail({ initialData: [12, 8, 3] , speed: "Off" });
      anim.doInsertBack(20);
    </script>
    <xi:include href="../../fragments/ds-linked-list-instructions.xml"/>
  </interactive>
  </activity>

  <p>
    Now, adding an element to the end of the list only takes a few steps, regardless of how long the list is. We do have to worry about one special case - inserting into an empty list. In that case, we need to make sure to set both the head and tail pointers to point to the new node. Here is what an implementation of <pf>insertEnd</pf> might look like:  
  </p>
  
  <listing>
    <title>insertEnd Implementation</title>
  <program>
    <![CDATA[
  template <typename T>
  void SinglyLinkedList<T>::insertEnd(T value) {
      // allocate new node on the heap. Store the address in "newNode"
      ListNode<T>* newNode = new ListNode<T>(value);
      if (size == 0) {
          // if the list is empty, new node is both head and tail
          head = newNode;
          tail = newNode;
      } else {
          // set old tail's next pointer to point to the new node
          tail->next = newNode;
          // make newNode the new tail
          tail = newNode;
      }
      size++;
  }
    ]]>
  </program>
  </listing>

  <p>This new capability comes with a cost. 
    Our existing functions also will need to worry about maintaining the tail pointer. Here are some new special cases we will need to handle:
    <ul>
      <li>When inserting into an empty list <pf>insertStart</pf> needs to set both the head and tail pointers to point to the new node.</li>
      <li>If <pf>removeAt</pf> is called on the index of the last node, we need to make sure to update the tail pointer.</li>
      <li>When removing the last node from the list (if size is 0 after removing), we need to make sure the tail pointer is set to <pf>nullptr</pf>. <pf>removeFront</pf> and <pf>removeAt</pf> both need to worry about this case.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>The logic for <pf>removeAt</pf> will now need to look like:</p>
  
  <program language="text">
    <![CDATA[
    if (index == 0) {
        removeFirst();
        return;
    }
    ListNode* current = head
    while (index > 1) {
        current = current->next
        index--
    }
    ListNode* toDelete = current->next
    current->next = toDelete->next
    if (toDelete == tail) {
        tail = current
    }
    delete toDelete
    size--
    ]]>
  </program>

  <p>
    We still can't efficiently remove an element from the end of the list. To remove the last element, we need to adjust the next pointer of the second-to-last node to be <pf>nullptr</pf> and adjust the tail pointer to point to that node as we delete the last one. But we have no way to reach the second-to-last node without starting at the head and walking through the list. To allow for this, we will need to add pointers that go backwards in the list as well, creating a doubly linked list.
  </p>


</section>